# Security Review — `app.js`

The application is a minimal Express server. While it is short, it has **several significant security gaps** across multiple OWASP Top 10 categories. Here is a structured finding-by-finding breakdown with concrete remediation code.

---

## 1. 🔴 Broken Access Control (OWASP A01) — Unauthenticated `/users` Endpoint

**Severity: High**

The `/users` route returns PII (names + email addresses) to **any unauthenticated caller** with no authorization check whatsoever.

```js
// ❌ Current — completely open
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([...]);
});
```

**Recommendation:** Add authentication middleware (e.g., JWT or session-based) and only allow authorized roles to access user data.

```js
// ✅ Fixed — JWT auth middleware example
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const authHeader = req.headers['authorization'];
  const token = authHeader && authHeader.split(' ')[1]; // "Bearer <token>"

  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });

  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET);
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Forbidden' });
  }
}

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  res.json([...]);
});
```

---

## 2. 🔴 Sensitive Data Exposure (OWASP A02) — PII Returned Without Encryption or Scoping

**Severity: High**

Even if auth were added, the endpoint returns full email addresses in plaintext JSON with no field scoping. Responses should expose the **minimum necessary data**, and the app should run over HTTPS.

```js
// ❌ Current — exposes full PII
{ id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' }

// ✅ Fixed — omit sensitive fields unless caller has elevated role
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  const users = getUsers(); // fetch from DB
  const safeUsers = users.map(({ id, name }) => ({ id, name })); // strip email
  res.json(safeUsers);
});
```

Also enforce HTTPS at the infrastructure level, or redirect inside the app:

```js
// ✅ Force HTTPS in production
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  if (process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production' && req.headers['x-forwarded-proto'] !== 'https') {
    return res.redirect(301, `https://${req.hostname}${req.originalUrl}`);
  }
  next();
});
```

---

## 3. 🔴 Security Misconfiguration (OWASP A05) — No Security Headers

**Severity: High**

Express ships with no protective HTTP headers by default. Without `helmet`, responses are missing headers like `Content-Security-Policy`, `X-Frame-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `X-Content-Type-Options`, etc.

```js
// ❌ Current — no security headers set
const app = express();

// ✅ Fixed — add helmet
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet()); // sets ~15 security headers automatically
```

---

## 4. 🟠 Identification and Authentication Failures (OWASP A07) — No Rate Limiting or Brute-Force Protection

**Severity: Medium**

There is no rate limiting on any endpoint. An attacker can enumerate the `/users` endpoint (or any future login/token endpoint) without throttling.

```js
// ✅ Fixed — add rate limiting
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // max 100 requests per IP per window
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
  message: { error: 'Too many requests, please try again later.' },
});

app.use(limiter); // apply globally, or scope to specific routes
```

---

## 5. 🟠 Injection Risk — No Body Parser / Input Validation (OWASP A03)

**Severity: Medium (latent — will become High when POST routes are added)**

The app has no body parsing middleware and no input validation library. Any future `POST`/`PUT` routes that read `req.body` will be vulnerable to injection unless validated from day one.

```js
// ✅ Fixed — add body parsing + validation now, before adding POST routes
const express = require('express');
const { body, param, validationResult } = require('express-validator');

app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' })); // parse JSON; limit body size to prevent DoS

// Example of a safe future POST /users route
app.post(
  '/users',
  requireAuth,
  body('name').isString().trim().isLength({ min: 1, max: 100 }).escape(),
  body('email').isEmail().normalizeEmail(),
  (req, res) => {
    const errors = validationResult(req);
    if (!errors.isEmpty()) {
      return res.status(422).json({ errors: errors.array() });
    }
    // safe to proceed
  }
);
```

---

## 6. 🟠 Information Disclosure via `/health` Endpoint

**Severity: Medium**

The `/health` endpoint exposes the server's real-time clock. While low risk alone, timestamp data can aid fingerprinting and timing-based attacks.

```js
// ❌ Current — leaks server timestamp to anonymous callers
res.json({ status: 'ok', timestamp: new Date().toISOString() });

// ✅ Fixed — omit timestamp (or gate it behind auth)
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'ok' });
});
```

---

## 7. 🟠 No CORS Policy (OWASP A05)

**Severity: Medium**

Without explicit CORS configuration, browser behavior is unpredictable across environments. An explicit allowlist prevents cross-origin abuse if this API is consumed by a browser client.

```js
// ✅ Fixed — explicit CORS policy
const cors = require('cors');

app.use(cors({
  origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGINS?.split(',') ?? [],
  methods: ['GET', 'POST', 'PUT', 'DELETE'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Content-Type', 'Authorization'],
  credentials: true,
}));
```

---

## 8. 🟡 Hardcoded Data (Scalability / Future Injection Risk)

**Severity: Low (now), High (if moved to DB without parameterized queries)**

The user list is currently hardcoded, which is safe. When this moves to a real database, SQL/NoSQL injection becomes a critical risk. Establish the pattern of parameterized queries now.

```js
// ✅ Use parameterized queries (example with pg)
const { Pool } = require('pg');
const pool = new Pool({ connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL });

app.get('/users', requireAuth, async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const { rows } = await pool.query('SELECT id, name FROM users'); // never interpolate user input
    res.json(rows);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err);
    res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' });
  }
});
```

---

## 9. 🟡 No Centralized Error Handler (Information Leakage)

**Severity: Low**

Unhandled errors will bubble up as Express default stack-trace responses, leaking internal details to clients.

```js
// ✅ Add a catch-all error handler as the LAST middleware
app.use((err, req, res, _next) => {
  const isDev = process.env.NODE_ENV !== 'production';
  console.error(err); // log internally
  res.status(err.status ?? 500).json({
    error: isDev ? err.message : 'Internal server error',
  });
});
```

---

