### 2. No Authentication or Authorization on Any Endpoint (OWASP A01 – Broken Access Control)

The `/users` endpoint returns a user list (including email addresses) with absolutely no authentication check. Any unauthenticated caller on the network gets full access.

```js
// CURRENT — completely open
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([{ id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' }, ...]);
});
```

**Recommendation:** Add an authentication middleware. Here's an example using JWT:

```js
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const authHeader = req.headers.authorization;
  if (!authHeader?.startsWith('Bearer ')) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Missing or invalid Authorization header' });
  }
  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(authHeader.slice(7), process.env.JWT_SECRET);
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Invalid or expired token' });
  }
}

// Apply to protected routes
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => { ... });
```

